# Build vs. Buy: Own Search Engine or Integrate Algolia?

## Context

**MarktLab** is a B2B marketplace for industrial wholesalers in DACH. Scale-up, 60 developers, €30M ARR, PostgreSQL-based, Next.js web app. Platform hosts 180,000 products from 400 suppliers, averaging 12 attributes per product.

Current search runs on PostgreSQL Full-Text-Search. User feedback: **poor relevance, no faceted filters, slow on complex queries**. Conversion on search results sits at 3.2% — industry benchmark: 8%+.

CPO has tasked Engineering: better search must go live in 6 months.

## Your Role

You are a **Senior Software Engineer** on the Platform team. Your Tech Lead asked you to submit a **Decision Doc**: Do we build search ourselves on Elasticsearch/OpenSearch, or buy Algolia/Typesense? Leadership team decides tomorrow afternoon based on your paper.

## Starting Position

**Team & resources:**
- 2 Senior Engineers (including you) could lead this project
- Additional 0.5 SRE capacity for infrastructure
- Budget: up to €120k in year 1, beyond that needs CFO sign-off

**Candidates:**

| Option | Type | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| Elasticsearch (self-hosted) | Build | Full control, no vendor lock-in | Ops burden, cluster tuning, 3–6 month build |
| Algolia | Buy (SaaS) | Live in 4–6 weeks, top search relevance out-of-box | €24k–€60k/year depending on traffic, vendor lock-in |
| Typesense (self-hosted) | Build-light | Open-source, faster deploy than ES | Less mature, smaller community |
| Pinecone / Weaviate (Vector) | Exotic | Semantic search possible | Overkill for current use case |

**Requirements from PM:**
- Faceted search (brand, price, lead time, category)
- Typo tolerance
- Autocomplete
- Sub-200ms P95 latency
- Admin interface for relevance tuning
- Multilingual (DE, EN — later IT, FR)

**Technical reality at MarktLab:**
- DevOps team is 2 people, currently no capacity for Elasticsearch cluster
- Product data updated 4x daily from supplier feeds (ETL via Airflow)
- No existing message queue; events run via DB polling
- Leadership allergic to "6-month engineering projects" — last internal build took 14 months and was later replaced with SaaS

## Your Task

Deliver a **2-page decision doc**:

1. **Recommendation** (first page, first paragraph — not at the end). Which option, why, in 3 sentences.
2. **Trade-off matrix**: 3 realistic options (cut ones you don''t take seriously) against 5–6 criteria: Time-to-Value, 3-year TCO, Ops Burden, Relevance Quality, Flexibility, Risk.
3. **Cost calculation**: 3-year TCO model (effort + infrastructure + licenses) for your recommended option.
4. **Migration plan** (rough phases, no Jira tickets): How do we get from PostgreSQL-FTS to the new solution without downtime?
5. **Risks & open questions**: What don''t you know yet, and how do you de-risk it?

## Guiding Questions

- What''s the riskiest assumption in your proposal? If it''s wrong, what does it cost?
- Leadership is "allergic" to long build projects. How much does that bias your purely technical recommendation — and is it legitimate?
- Algolia costs maybe €150k over 3 years. Two senior engineers for 6 months cost fully loaded ~€250k. Why do engineers often still think "we''ll build it ourselves"?
- What''s **reversible vs. irreversible** here? If Algolia triples in price in 2 years, how quickly can you exit?
- What would you deliberately *not* do, even if others suggest it (e.g., vector DB for "AI search" because it''s trendy)?

## Match Info

**Fits:** Software Engineer (Backend / Full-stack), Technical Product Manager, DevOps Engineer, Site Reliability Engineer, Data Engineer, Mobile Developer, Technical Account Manager
**Tests primarily:** Architecture Judgment, Business Awareness, Technical Writing, Pragmatism
**Industry fit:** Tech, SaaS, all data-intensive platforms', 50, 'intermediate', '{"Architecture Trade-offs","Cost-Benefit Analysis","Technical Writing","Pragmatism vs. Engineering Ambition"}'),
  ('cs-14-ml-production-tradeoff', 'b45565ba-2477-58db-89e1-9cf250fff089', 'New Recommender Model: 3% Better Metric, Double Latency — Deploy?', '<img src="logos/cs-14-ml-production-tradeoff.png" alt="ReadWave logo" width="120" align="right" />

# New Recommender Model: 3% Better Metric, Double Latency — Deploy?

## Context

**ReadWave** is a streaming platform for audiobooks and podcasts in DACH. 2.8 million active users, €42M ARR. The personalization engine drives 60% of all play events — recommendations on the homepage, in the "Keep Listening" feed, and in push notifications.

The current production model is a Two-Tower Neural Net (retrieval) + Gradient-Boosted-Trees (ranking), live for 18 months. The ML team built a new **Transformer-based candidate**.

## Your Role

You are a **Senior ML Engineer** who built the new model. Tomorrow is a decision meeting with Head of ML, Head of Product, and VP Engineering: **Deploy yes or no?**

## Starting Position — The Numbers

**Offline evaluation** (holdout over 4 weeks, n=12M interactions):

| Metric | Baseline | New Model | Delta |
|---|---|---|---|
| Recall@20 | 0.312 | 0.327 | **+4.8%** |
| NDCG@10 | 0.418 | 0.441 | **+5.5%** |
| Diversity-Score (Intra-List) | 0.61 | 0.54 | **-11.5%** |
| CTR-predicted | 0.093 | 0.096 | +3.2% |

**Production constraints:**

| | Baseline | New |
|---|---|---|
| P50 Latency | 34 ms | **78 ms** |
| P95 Latency | 68 ms | **142 ms** |
| Inference cost / 1M calls | €2.10 | **€6.40** |
| Model size | 180 MB | **1.2 GB** |
| Monthly inference budget now | €28k | projected €85k |

**Organizational context signals:**
- Head of Product has Q2 OKR: "Session-Time +8%" — pressure on ML team rising
- VP Engineering just finished budget discussions, will eye +300% inference budget skeptically
- SRE team reported last week: current GPU instance is at 72% utilization — more inference load needs capacity planning
- Analytics team has fragmentary doubts: Diversity drop could harm long-term user retention (filter-bubble effect)
- 2 years ago, similar launch looked good offline but went negative in A/B test (+costs, -retention)

## Your Task

Prepare for tomorrow:

1. **Your recommendation** in **one sentence** (not "it depends"). Justification follows.
2. **A/B-test design**, if you recommend testing: Traffic %, duration, guardrails (auto-stop criteria)? Primary and secondary metrics?
3. **Offline-to-online gap plan**: Which 3 things could go wrong between offline evaluation and online behavior? How do you address them before launch?
4. **Cost optimization** (only if relevant): If latency/cost are the blocker — what are 2 realistic ways to make the model cheaper before launch? (Distillation, quantization, caching, candidate-retrieval changes)
5. **Kill criteria**: Under what A/B-test results do you abort and kill the project?

## Guiding Questions

- Offline metrics are *proxies* for online behavior. Which of your offline metrics has the weakest track record correlating with business metrics (session time, retention)?
- The diversity drop is -11.5% — sounds like a filter bubble. Is that a feature (more relevance → better engagement) or a bug (users see too much similarity, lose interest)?
- Head of Product needs a win. How do you keep that pressure from distorting your technical judgment?
- +300% inference budget: What ROI case do you show VP Engineering to get approval?
- What''s a **middle option** — not "deploy" or "kill", but something like "deploy to power users only," "hybrid model," "distilled model"?

## Match Info

**Fits:** Machine Learning Engineer, Data Scientist, Software Engineer (Backend), Data Engineer, Analytics Engineer, Technical Product Manager
**Tests primarily:** ML Engineering Judgment, System Thinking, Business Translation, Risk Management
**Industry fit:** Tech platforms with personalization, Streaming, E-Commerce, Ad-Tech', 45, 'intermediate', '{"Offline-Online-Gap Understanding","A/B-Test-Design","System-Performance Trade-offs","Stakeholder Communication of ML Metrics"}'),
