# Policy Edge Case: Should Fitness Challenges Stay on the Platform?

## Context

**Pulsem** is a social-video platform (8.2M MAU in DACH, primarily 14–29). Content type: short videos (15–60s), fitness is a top category. Existing community guidelines prohibit "content that glorifies self-harm or encourages risky behavior" — but fitness challenges fall in a gray area.

**The specific case:** The hashtag **#75hard** (challenge: 75 days of 2× daily 45-min training, strict diet, 3.7L water, 10 pages of reading, no cheat meals) has 780,000 videos on Pulsem. Medical experts in 2 German media reports last week criticized the challenge: overloading, triggers eating-disorder tendencies in teens. Two medical associations have contacted Pulsem.

Your Trust & Safety Head has asked you: by next Wednesday, a policy recommendation. Leadership has to decide.

## Your Role

You are a **Trust & Safety Analyst** at Pulsem, 3rd year in role.

## Situation

**What you know about the content (sample of 500 random #75hard videos):**

| Video type | Share | Character |
|---|---|---|
| "Day X" documentation | 68% | Mostly benign, sometimes inspiring, sometimes visibly exhausted |
| "Transformations" (before/after body comparison) | 14% | Body-highlighting, promotes comparison culture |
| Tips for sticking with it | 9% | Neutral |
| Critical / ironic voices | 4% | Warning against challenge, testimonial |
| Extreme / risky behavior | 5% | Visible overload, pain, "mental toughness above all" |

**What you know about the users:**
- 52% of #75hard creators are under 21
- 18% have age flagged as "under 16" (Minor flag)
- Comment analysis: frequent questions from teens ("I''m 15, can I do this?"), also critiques from other users

**What other platforms have done:**
- **TikTok**: has not banned #75hard, but adds warning label and shows helpline info on search
- **Instagram**: no specific policy, but reels with risky content are demonetized
- **YouTube**: age gate for certain extreme fitness challenges

**Internal stakeholders:**
- **Product Lead Discovery**: "If we remove 780k videos we lose massive engagement and user satisfaction"
- **Legal**: "We have no DSA duty to remove this, as long as it''s not ''illegal content'' — but we might face pressure from DSA coordinators"
- **Brand/PR**: "Medical association critique is a real risk. 2 press inquiries already in"
- **Creator Success**: "#75hard creators are often micro-influencers with engaged followers, who also make other (healthier) content. We can''t blanket-penalize"

**Policy options:**

A) **Full hashtag ban** — clear signal, massive engagement loss and creator anger
B) **Age gate on #75hard content** — under-18 users don''t see the hashtag
C) **Warning label + resource panel** before every video with the hashtag (links to BZgA resources, info on healthy training)
D) **Algorithmic demotion** — videos remain but not actively pushed in Feed/For-You
E) **Subtle policy change**: only remove videos with "extreme behavior" character, keep normal "Day X" documentation
F) **Do nothing**: observe, keep reviewing, no precedent-setting decision
G) **Hybrid**: combination of B + C + engagement with creator community

