# Counterfeit Spike on the Marketplace: Stop the Bleeding Before Q4

## Context

**Bostro** is a European general-merchandise marketplace (~9,000 third-party sellers, GMV €410M/year, four major categories: Electronics, Fashion, Home, Beauty). In the last 8 weeks, **counterfeit complaints have tripled** — from a baseline of ~140/month to 460/month. Refund volume is up 22%. Two well-known brands have publicly threatened to delist. Q4 (your biggest quarter, 38% of annual GMV) starts in 7 weeks.

You''ve been asked by the VP of Marketplace to lead a cross-functional response: triage the immediate problem, plan the Q4 protections, and draft a longer-term seller-trust roadmap.

## Your Role

You are a **Marketplace Operations Manager** (3 years at Bostro, started as a Merchandising Analyst). You report to the VP Marketplace and have working relationships with Trust & Safety, Category Management, and Seller Operations.

## Situation

**What you''ve found from data analysis:**

| Signal | Detail |
|---|---|
| Counterfeit complaints by category | 71% Beauty, 18% Electronics, 9% Fashion, 2% Home |
| New seller cohort | Sellers onboarded in last 6 months are responsible for 64% of complaints |
| Geographic clustering | 38% of complaints trace to ~80 sellers, mostly registered in 3 EU countries |
| Listing patterns | Many of these sellers price at 30-40% below brand authorized retailer |
| Onboarding KYC | Bostro''s seller verification was loosened 9 months ago to drive seller acquisition |
| Brand reports | 7 brand-rights-owners filed VeRo notices last week, vs. ~1/week historically |
| Buyer reviews | 4-star average has slipped to 3.6 in Beauty |

**Internal context:**
- Bostro''s growth strategy this year was "seller acquisition first" — KYC was relaxed, listing approval was sped up. Sellers signed 2.4× faster than last year.
- Beauty is the highest-margin category (24% take-rate vs. 12-18% in others)
- The Q4 forecast assumes Beauty grows 35% YoY
- The CEO''s response so far: "Don''t blow up our seller numbers"
- Trust & Safety team has 8 people (was 6 a year ago, head wanted to grow to 14)
- Category Management is run by the head of merchandising who pushed for fast seller acquisition

**Stakeholders:**
- **VP Marketplace (your boss)**: wants action but also wants to protect category numbers
- **Head of Beauty Category**: defensive — these sellers are her growth engine
- **Trust & Safety Lead**: has been warning for 6 months that loosened KYC was a problem; now feels vindicated and slightly burned-out
- **Brand-relations head**: pressure from L''Oréal, P&G, several niche brands; threatened delistings
- **CEO**: wants the issue resolved without "killing the marketplace"
- **Legal**: liability under DSA (Digital Services Act) is now in play — failing to act on notices has direct legal consequence

**Available levers:**
1. Suspend the 80 high-complaint sellers immediately (impact: ~6% of Beauty GMV gone)
2. Re-verify KYC on all 6-month-cohort sellers (180k listings affected, 4-week project)
3. Re-introduce stricter onboarding for new sellers (slows growth)
4. Brand-authorization gates on key brands (only authorized resellers can list these brands)
5. Test-buy program (Bostro buys samples from suspect sellers, verifies authenticity)
6. Public communication to buyers and brands about the response
7. Refund-to-buyer expansion (no questions asked) to protect customer experience while you fix supply

## Your Task

Action plan in 1.5 pages:

1. **The first 7 days**: which actions ship immediately? (Lever-by-lever specifics, not "we''ll improve trust")
2. **Q4 protection** (next 7 weeks): what do you do to ensure the Beauty category survives Q4 without further damage?
3. **The 80 high-complaint sellers**: do you suspend all, suspend some, or re-verify? Justify.
4. **Brand-authorization gating**: applies to which brands and at what threshold? What''s the trade-off?
5. **Internal narrative**: how do you align the Head of Beauty (whose numbers will take a hit) and the CEO (who wants to protect numbers)?
6. **DSA compliance**: how do you make sure you''re handling brand notices within legal timeframes?
7. **Long-term roadmap (post-Q4)**: 3-4 changes to seller-trust architecture (tiered onboarding, behavioral-based scoring, etc.)

## Guiding Questions

- Suspending 80 sellers tomorrow is the cleanest move but loses 6% of Beauty GMV at the worst possible time. What''s the structured way to think about that trade-off?
- The relaxed KYC 9 months ago was a strategic mistake. Naming that internally is politically costly. How do you write the diagnosis honestly without making it a blame exercise?
- Test-buys are powerful evidence but expensive (cost + time). Where do you target them?
- Buyer trust takes years to build, weeks to lose. What''s the buyer-facing communication approach?

